{"author":{"id":"4bb6c1767e50694cfde61856db22bf137d1651e8a0b5ca858c486db3dd02f280"},"ops":[{"type":1,"timestamp":1774290730,"nonce":"3FwUQKb0RiqbfsY2EOju0VwA2jA=","title":"Supplementary experiment: formal comparison of BCS/DAI/PAI-ASF training methods","message":"## Summary\n\nDesign for a supplementary paper experiment demonstrating the formal differences between the three training methods through behavioral and computational comparisons. Analyzed by Opus, critiqued by Gemini.\n\n## Training Protocol\n\n3 methods x 2 perturbation types (curl fields + constant fields) = 6 training conditions, 5 replicates each (default ensemble). All use default hyperparameters from default.yml — only hps.method varies.\n\n**Gemini addition**: Include a No-SISU baseline (same perturbation distribution but no contextual signal). This establishes the \"feedback only\" performance floor, allowing statements like \"DAI improves via feedforward cancellation, PAI-ASF via feedback gain modulation that the No-SISU model cannot access.\" This adds 2 more runs (curl + constant) for 8 total.\n\n## Evaluation Protocol\n\n### Probe 1: SISU-Amplitude Matrix\n5 SISU levels x 5 perturbation amplitudes = 25 conditions per method per perturbation type. Reveals the shape of SISU-performance relationship (step vs linear vs smooth curve).\n\n### Probe 2: SISU Extrapolation\nExtended SISU range [-1.0, -0.5, 0, 0.25, 0.5, 0.75, 1.0, 1.5, 2.0, 3.0] at fixed perturbation (1x training std).\n\n### Probe 3: SISU-Perturbation Mismatch\n- SISU=0 with perturbation present: does network \"trust\" SISU and fail to compensate?\n- SISU=1 with no perturbation: does network generate phantom compensatory forces?\nThis directly tests feedforward prediction (DAI) vs gain modulation (PAI-ASF).\n\n### Probe 4: Feedback Gain Curves\nBrief feedback impulses (position and velocity) at each SISU level. Measure corrective response magnitude. PAI-ASF should show graded gain increase; DAI minimal gain modulation.\n\n**Gemini enhancement**: Also use a \"stiffness probe\" — tiny 10ms pulse perturbation during reach, measure recovery speed vs SISU. This is the direct behavioral correlate of feedback gain.\n\n### Probe 5: Cross-Perturbation Generalization\nTrain on curl, evaluate on constant (and vice versa) at SISU=1. DAI should fail (feedforward cancellation is type-specific); PAI-ASF should partially generalize.\n\n### Probe 6 (Gemini): Mid-Reach Perturbation Change\nChange perturbation direction or type mid-reach. DAI should produce large \"jerk\" (feedforward model suddenly wrong); PAI-ASF should handle more gracefully (reactive high-gain strategy).\n\n## Key Predictions\n\n| Measure | BCS | DAI | PAI-ASF |\n|---------|-----|-----|---------|\n| SISU-error curve shape | Step function | Linear/smooth | Smooth monotonic |\n| Phantom forces (SISU=1, no pert) | Minimal | Large (feedforward) | Minimal |\n| Feedback gain modulation with SISU | Binary switch | Weak | Graded increase |\n| Cross-pert generalization | Poor | Very poor | Partial |\n| Extrapolation beyond [0,1] | Chaotic | Linear then unstable | Monotonic, saturating |\n| Initial command magnitude at high SISU | Low | High (feedforward) | Low-moderate |\n\n## Analysis Plan\n\nQuantities: end-position error, max lateral deviation, peak parallel velocity, movement duration, max net force, initial command magnitude (first 2 steps), peak corrective force after feedback impulse, recovery speed from pulse perturbation.\n\nStatistics: Two-way interaction (method x SISU) via linear mixed-effects models. Random effect = replicate. Key contrasts: grading test (error vs SISU regression slope), mismatch cost, phantom force magnitude, feedback gain slope.\n\n## Figure Plan\n\n**Figure S1**: Behavioral signatures (4 panels) — trajectories across methods/SISU values, error vs SISU curves, initial command magnitude, mismatch conditions.\n\n**Figure S2**: Feedback gain modulation (3 panels) — force profiles after impulse by SISU, peak corrective force vs SISU per method, position vs velocity channel gains.\n\n**Figure S3**: Extrapolation and generalization (3 panels) — extended SISU range error curves, cross-pert generalization matrix, force profiles for cross-pert conditions.\n\n**Figure S4**: Strategy map (Gemini suggestion, replaces radar plot) — 2D scatter: X = \"feedforward-ness\" (mismatch trial deviation), Y = \"feedback-ness\" (pulse recovery speed). DAI should appear bottom-right, PAI-ASF top-left.\n\n**Gemini note**: Show individual seeds (light colored lines) behind means in all figures. Builds reviewer trust that behavior is method property, not lucky initialization.\n\n## Practical Notes\n\n- 8 training runs total (6 method x pert + 2 no-SISU baseline)\n- All infrastructure exists except: batched training config varying method axis (YAML change), cross-pert evaluation override (small code change), and multi-panel figure composition\n- No Feedbax changes needed\n- If compute allows, increase to N=10 replicates (Gemini recommendation for quantification)\n\n## Open Questions from Gemini\n\n1. \"Does PAI-ASF really have aleatoric uncertainty?\" — Yes: perturbation = beta * sigma * epsilon where epsilon is Gaussian. SISU = beta but epsilon is unknown. The realization is unpredictable given SISU.\n\n2. \"GRUs are lazy — might PAI-ASF learn a safe average trajectory rather than genuine gain modulation?\" — Worth verifying via the Jacobian analysis. If PAI-ASF modulates the recurrent Jacobian eigenvalues (system stiffness/reactivity) rather than just shifting the fixed point (bias), that's strong evidence for genuine robustness.\n\n3. \"Signal-dependent noise might be needed to make high-gain strategy costly\" — The existing motor noise and control cost terms partially address this, but explicit signal-dependent noise could strengthen the argument.\n\nCo-authored-by: Claude Opus 4.6 \u003cnoreply@anthropic.com\u003e, Gemini 3.1 Pro Preview \u003cnoreply@google.com\u003e","files":null}]}